candidates.name: Lighthouse Park

reviews.text: We stopped by here when we were staying down on the Everett waterfront for the weekend. Great park for the kids! Lots of good pals for walking, running. Brought the kids bikes and let them bike around. Lots of great beaches for the kids to play in the water as well. If you‚Äôre in the area I highly recommend this park!
I like this park and my kids too except parking lot

Adequate pay parking. We scored a spot close to the water. Great rocky beach with lots of driftwood for sitting. We happened to go just when a humpback whale was putting on an awesome show!! It was amazing!! We could hear the fins flapping on the water. It was fun to watch and hear everyone on the beach going ‚Äúooh, awe!!‚Äù
What a sight!

Beautiful park and beach. One of the few spots in the county where they bonfire pits as well! You gotta pay for parking but it is well worth it to support this amazing park. The entrance to the ferry has changed so now there's a lot less traffic in from of Ivar's. The whole area has come a long way

A really nice place to see marine life and have gatherings. Locals and visitors love it. Ivar's, Anthonys, and diamond knot are all right next to the beach which makes for a really easy dining choice. If you are around this area you should definitely check it out!

candidates.formatted_address: 5829 E Rutter Ave, Spokane, WA 99212, United States
candidates.name: Historic Flight Foundation

reviews.text: What a fun museum we happened to find after breakfast. I had the best time taking my three year old in. Thanks for a great time

What an amazing place. So much history, all restored to original. There was a knowledgeable guide to explain the aircraft. Two planes were outside and available to go inside. Not a place for active children.
What a fantastic museum! It's small, but packed with an amazing assortment of planes, all in amazing condition. Glad I took the time to visit!
Awesome collection and the people were great. We got to see a B25 take off and land. The place is super clean and well organized.

I was able to experience a DC3 flight on 4 Sept 21... Amazing aircraft and experience!!! 5 Stars. The B25 was landing just before we took off. Thanks Mr. Sessions for bringing your flight museum to Spokane Felts Field. üëçüëçüëç

candidates.formatted_address: 12303 Cyrus Way Suite 107, Mukilteo, WA 98275, United States
candidates.name: Sno-King Visitation

reviews.text:
Despite the factory tour being closed, the backstage pass film is a good way to find out more about the history and operations at this site. It's no substitute for a real tour though! There was a Q&A session at the end which was a good opportunity to ask questions, although some of the answers given weren't very informative.

The museum and viewing deck are good, so this is a good way to spend a few hours just half an hour outside Seattle.

Great place to visit, for aircraft enthusiast!
Only disappointing, not being able to go into the factory to see the actual manufacturing process.
But, it is perfectly understandable, as their staff are of utmost priority.
Nevertheless, the presenters were very knowledgable and presented very professionally! Well done!!
You did an awesome presentation!! üëèüëèüëèüëè

If I am able to visit this place and 3 years later remember exactly what was there, then I know it was the best. If you haven‚Äôt gone yet, let this museum steal your money from you to have some fun! It‚Äôs great especially with kids, and when they are young.

I was surprised at how informative and interesting this tour was (in that the factory tours are currently closed).

The building has many exhibits including hands-on (mostly for youth).  There is a drone area that you can practice flying.

You also have access to a roof top, which provides excellent views of Paine Field and has a radio broadcasting the tower traffic.

The best part for us was the one hour presentation, which was hosted by staff . You could ask questions and interact about the history and the assembly process.  It's not like the actual factory tour, but it's still very informative.

If you travel to Boeing to be able to lay eyes on the largest building in the world, prepare for disappointment. Boeing decided to stop the tours when COVID hit, but subsequently never decided to resume them. So what you can do is pay handsomely to watch a video about what you WOULD have seen, but can‚Äôt.

This is a simple management decision. If the federal government is no longer requiring masks on flights, surely you can conduct tours in a building as big as the outdoors.  I can only assume that it‚Äôs more profitable NOT to conduct the tours and instead charge people to watch a video, then send them to the gift shop.

Either way, don‚Äôt waste your time.

Be sure and tour the lighthouse and visit the park.
Fun place to visit

This is a lovely park,  with plenty of room for your pooch to run. There is also a shy dog area. Both dog areas have agility equipment. There are nice trails into Japanese gulch for walking on leash, so the humans can get some exercise too! It can be muddy though, so bring your boots.
Update on 7/3/22- they have put down some bark,  and it looks like they will be putting down more fresh bark in the near future.
We absolutely love this place. For little dogs they love walking through the hills we spend an easy 2-3hrs hiking.

Best one I've been to in the area. Be sure to bring your poop üéí bags for your pup and nearly every one else's too. Nice benches where folks sit and ignore their dogs.  Just kidding, kinda. I'd go back!

Nice big open space with clear line of sight for the whole dog park. There's some fun agility equipment in there and a separate section for small dogs. The Japanese Gulch trails nearby are also great for hiking with the dogs. No potable water and the parking lot can fill up quickly.
I grew up in this area so I have a deep love for this place.
